    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Eaton Tuesdy Morg 12 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest W. I do not exactly know yet what we are to do today. We were to have gone &amp; lunched at Brampton (8 miles off) with the Jones's, Hewetts' &amp; Achesons girls. But the day is so tempestuous that this is at an end. I suppose</p>
      <p>I shall know by &amp; bye, before post goes out in the evening, more of our plans.</p>
      <p>I believe I am to go to Cambridge tomorrow certainly, tho' I fancy in a chaise instead of on horseback, as it appears unlikely I can get any beasts about here. The Hen talks of coming to Cambridge to fetch me, when she leaves this, &amp; then our going straight</p>
      <p>to Leicestershire without returning to this neighbourhood. I think this would be a nice plan; as I know she is very desirous of seeing your Sisters &amp; Mrs Calliphronas. But she is kindly anxious that I should have as long a time as possible with them; knowing I should enjoy it.</p>
      <p>Many thanks for your nice letter this morning. The Hen has in many respects so firm, strong,</p>
      <p>&amp; manly a mind and understanding, that I often feel surprised at the little tiny weaknesses, which certainly are sometimes the plague &amp; injury of herself &amp; whoever is with her; not the less from their being often about very small, &amp; for the moment even trivial, matters. I think there has been originally no doubt the same tendency, but that ill-health &amp; unfortunate circumstances</p>
      <p>have much exaggerated it. I fancy her very different the last 3 days.</p>
      <p>Of course I exist myself to save her all trouble; &amp; arrange everything for her, as much as possible.</p>
      <p>Indeed I believe I do more for her than either her maid or footman.</p>
      <p>This morning I have been busy making all comfortable for her against she is dressed; &amp; I now expect her in every minute.</p>
      <p>I found she disliked</p>
      <p>the Sitting-Room here. It was a nasty place, down stairs, thro' drafty cold passages, &amp; very dull, fusty, &amp; gloomy.</p>
      <p>She was vexed in bed this morning about it, &amp; said her health would suffer; &amp; there was no up-stairs Sitting- -Room in the Inn. I sent for the landlady, &amp; have made a very comfortable Sitting-Room of a Bed-room; &amp; have had</p>
      <p>luncheon prepared for her.</p>
      <p>This was all very easy; but would never have been decided on without me. And besides, it does really require an active person, like myself, to make the people do what one wants, alter the furniture for instance, &amp;c. I wish the Hen had a nice, clever maid, who was attached to her. This would do much as to her daily comfort &amp; health. I tell you these</p>
      <p>little trifles, because you will then imagine our way of life and occupations just now. And besides, I have to events or great things to relate.--</p>
      <p>I wait entirely on myself. Besides that this is really necessary, because my mother's stupid &amp; dilatory maid ought not to have anything to do but wait on her, I also think it very good for one sometimes to be obliged to stir oneself</p>
    </div></body>
